Cardiac myocytes are non-dividing cells, which makes them resistant to chemotherapy since most chemotherapeutic agents target rapidly dividing cells. The other options consist of rapidly dividing cells and are therefore more susceptible to chemotherapy.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Among the options, cardiac myocytes are the most resistant to chemotherapy. This is because they are terminally differentiated cells and have a low turnover rate, so they are less affected by drugs that target rapidly dividing cells. In contrast, enterocytes, hair follicle cells, and liver hepatocytes all have high turnover rates and are therefore more susceptible to chemotherapy.
